# jq SMS Backup Cheatsheet

## Inspect JSON Structure

```bash
jq '.[0] | keys' sms_backup.json
```

Shows all fields present in a single SMS message object.

---

## Convert Timestamps to Human Readable Dates

```bash
jq '.[] | {date: (.date|tonumber/1000|strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")), body, address}' sms_backup.json
```

Converts the SMS timestamp from milliseconds to a readable date format and prints key fields.

---

## Display Messages as a Chat Log

```bash
jq -r '.[] |
  ((.date|tonumber/1000|strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")) +
  " | " +
  (if .type=="1" then .address else "Me" end) +
  ": " +
  .body)' sms_backup.json
```

Formats messages like a chronological chat conversation.

---

## Filter Messages From a Specific Contact

```bash
jq '.[] | select(.address=="+15555555555")' sms_backup.json
```

Shows only messages associated with a specific phone number.

---

## Extract Only Sent Messages

```bash
jq '.[] | select(.type=="2")' sms_backup.json
```

Filters messages so only outgoing (sent) messages are displayed.

---

## Remove Unwanted Metadata Fields

```bash
jq 'del(.[] .subject)' sms_backup.json > sms_clean.json
```

Removes the `subject` field (often proto metadata) from all messages.

---

## Export Messages to CSV

```bash
jq -r '.[] |
  [.date, .address, .body] |
  @csv' sms_backup.json
```

Converts SMS data into CSV format for spreadsheets or further analysis.

---

## Count Messages Per Contact

```bash
jq -r '.[].address' sms_backup.json | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr
```

Counts how many messages exist for each phone number.

---

## Find the Largest Conversations

```bash
jq -r '.[].address' sms_backup.json | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr | head
```

Displays the contacts with the most messages.

---

## Sort Messages Chronologically

```bash
jq 'sort_by(.date)' sms_backup.json > sorted_sms.json
```

Sorts all messages by timestamp and saves the result to a new JSON file.

---

## Detect Group Conversations

```bash
jq '.[] | select(.recipients | length > 1)' sms_backup.json
```

Identifies messages that involve multiple recipients (group chats).

---

## Group Messages by Contact

```bash
jq 'group_by(.address)' sms_backup.json
```

Groups all messages into arrays based on the contact phone number.

---

## Print Conversations Grouped by Contact

```bash
jq -r '
group_by(.address)[] |
"===== Conversation with " + .[0].address + " =====",
(.[] |
  ((.date|tonumber/1000|strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")) +
  " | " +
  (if .type=="1" then .address else "Me" end) +
  ": " +
  .body)),
""
' sms_backup.json
```

Formats grouped messages into readable conversations per contact.

---

## Prepare Conversations for Splitting Into Files

```bash
jq -r '
group_by(.address)[] |
  (.[0].address) as $a |
  .[] |
  [$a,
   (.date|tonumber/1000|strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")),
   (if .type=="1" then $a else "Me" end),
   .body] |
  @tsv
' sms_backup.json
```

Exports messages grouped by contact in tab-separated format for processing or splitting into individual files.

